<Base title="ENTITYFILE — ostk governance" description="The trust constitution of your OS instance. Establishes identity chains and access tiers.">
  <div class="container">
    <h1>ENTITYFILE</h1>
    <p class="lead">The trust constitution of your OS instance. Written once. Governs who can do what.</p>

    <h2>What it is</h2>
    <p>
      ENTITYFILE establishes the trust relationships between all actors in your OS:
      you (human), the kernel, agents, and CI. It defines identity chains, signing authorities,
      and capability tiers. Most developers don't need it initially — solo use defaults to T2 trust.
      Teams, CI pipelines, and multi-agent setups need it.
    </p>
    <p>Location: <code>.haystack/ENTITYFILE</code></p>

    <h2>Trust tiers</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Tier</th><th>Who</th><th>Capabilities</th><th>Identity proof</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>T0</strong></td>
          <td>Human operator</td>
          <td>Full — including modifying ENTITYFILE itself</td>
          <td>GPG key, locally held</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>T1</strong></td>
          <td>Verified agent or CI</td>
          <td>Write to source, run agents, delegate needles</td>
          <td>SSH or GPG key, cross-signed by T0</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>T2</strong></td>
          <td>Named agent (alias only)</td>
          <td>Read + limited write, no governance changes</td>
          <td>Alias in ENTITYFILE, no key required</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>T3</strong></td>
          <td>Anonymous</td>
          <td>Read only</td>
          <td>None</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Example</h2>
    <pre><code># ENTITYFILE

## Kernel
- name: haystack
- version: 1.0
- authority: T0 human → kernel → agents

## Identities

- handle: @scott
  type: human
  key: 955AF54E        # GPG fingerprint
  tier: T0

- handle: @haystack.prime
  type: kernel
  key: 99B076C9        # kernel root key
  tier: T1

- handle: @ci
  type: agent
  key: 6893C46C        # subordinate CI key, cross-signed by kernel
  tier: T1

- handle: @guest-agent
  type: agent
  tier: T2             # named but no key required</code></pre>

    <h2>When you need it</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Setup</th><th>Need ENTITYFILE?</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Solo developer, one machine</td><td>No — defaults work</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Solo developer, GPG identity needed</td><td>Optional — sign HUMANFILE instead</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Team with shared repo</td><td>Yes — establish T0 owner and T1 team members</td></tr>
        <tr><td>CI pipeline dispatching agents</td><td>Yes — CI key needs T1 registration</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Multiple humans with different trust levels</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>The negotiate protocol</h2>
    <p>
      Changes to ENTITYFILE require ceremony. You cannot unilaterally modify it —
      even as T0. The protocol:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>File an offer describing the change (<code>.haystack/offers/</code>)</li>
      <li>Counter-party reviews and responds</li>
      <li>Both parties sign with their keys</li>
      <li>Merge with <code>--no-ff</code> to preserve the ceremony in git history</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      This prevents silent governance changes. Every trust change is auditable.
    </p>

    <h2>Authority chain</h2>
    <p>
      Trust flows downward: <strong>T0 (human) → kernel → agents</strong>.
      The human is the root of trust. The kernel is the trust broker.
      Agents operate within the bounds the human defines via HUMANFILE and ENTITYFILE.
    </p>
    <p>
      No agent can elevate its own trust tier. No agent can modify ENTITYFILE.
      The human is always the final authority.
    </p>

